tmux workspace (tw) lessons

pane_title is not reliable for tagging panes. TUI programs like btop overwrite
it via OSC escape sequences immediately after opening. Use tmux pane user
variables (`set-option -p -t <pane> @key value` / `#{@key}` in formats) for
persistent, process-safe pane tagging.

Use window IDs (`#{window_id}`, format `@N`) when storing cross-window
references in persistent state (e.g. TW_PANE_STACK). Window names can be
changed and indices shift when windows are added or removed; IDs are stable for
the life of the tmux server.

tmux run-shell hands its string to `sh -c` which word-splits on spaces. Protect
paths: `run-shell "'$path'"` — single-quotes inside the double-quoted outer
string so `sh` sees a quoted path.

A zoomed pane (`prefix+z`) reports `pane_width == win_width` and
`pane_height == win_height`, identical to a sole pane. Check
`#{window_zoomed_flag}` before any sole-pane dimension comparison.

In a `while` loop that pops a stack and attempts a recoverable operation:
every skip path must `continue`, not fall through. A missing `continue` after
a failed `join-pane` caused the loop to exit, permanently orphaning the saved
window with no stack entry and no error.

`tmux split-window -P -F "#{pane_id}" 2>&1` is risky: tmux warnings on success
pollute the captured pane ID. Use `2>/dev/null` when capturing a pane ID from
split-window.

