Math dependency graph viewer lessons

Treat the viewer as an interactive editing surface, not just a static graph
render. Keep semantic graph data, visual state, and user layout state separate.
Most regressions came from using one state variable or one reset path for
multiple user intentions.

Selection and hover should use the same visual language. Hover is temporary
strong emphasis; selection is persistent weaker emphasis plus an explicit
marker. Avoid one-off effects that do not belong to that scale.

Preserve the user's mental map. Dragging one cell should only affect that
cell's incident edges; broader rerouting or relayout feels like the graph
changed under the user.

Manual node positions are first-class state. Any full render, reload, filter
change, reset, or edge redraw must account for them before deciding where edges
belong.

Do not trust native browser affordances for important controls. Disabled
buttons do not reliably expose hover help, so tooltips need enabled wrappers or
custom UI.

Macro support should follow the TeX source graph, including local classes and
packages, rather than hardcoding paper-specific command names.

Tests need to cover behavior, not only generated strings. String tests are
useful for template regressions, but interaction bugs need browser-level smoke
coverage where the environment supports it.

The next refactor should be structural, not behavioral: name the viewer's
template sections, document the state model, and keep routing modes explicit.
